  values ('bf1286bf-79ef-5946-ab40-2c6c5db38598', '2209bbbb-6204-5e62-bbe5-2ef3fa2f036b', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 8, 'mon'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:
Materials: “Cinderella” (a simplified version)
Lesson:
Hook (3 mins): Ask, “Can anyone name a favorite fairy tale?” Write a few student suggestions on the board.
Teach (4 mins):
Remind students that conflicts in stories are the problems that the characters face.
Explain that conflicts can happen between characters (Character vs. Character), or between a character and something else, like nature or themselves.
Mentor Text (6 mins): Read a brief retelling of “Cinderella”. Ask:
“What is the conflict in this story?”
Guide students to identify Character vs. Character (Cinderella and her stepmother/stepsisters).
Ask, “Do you think there could be other conflicts in the story?” (Possible answers: Character vs. Self - Cinderella’s feelings of sadness, or Character vs. Society - Cinderella not being allowed to go to the ball.)

Rotations:
See list from Sunday or the differentiation section below.', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: 📘 Reading Literature (RL)
CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RL.5.3 Compare and contrast two or more characters, settings, or events in a story or drama, drawing on specific details in the text (e.g., how characters interact).
EE.RL.5.3 Identify details that describe characters, settings, or events in a story.
📝 Language (L)
CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.L.5.2.AUse punctuation to separate items in a series.
EE.L.5.2.A Use ending punctuation when writing a sentence.
🔤 Reading Foundational Skills (RF)
CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.5.3.C Use context to confirm or self-correct word recognition and understanding, rereading as necessary.
EE.RF.5.3.CUse context to confirm word recognition and understanding.
CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.5.3Know and apply grade-level phonics and word analysis skills in decoding words.
EE.RF.5.3Use letter-sound knowledge and syllabication patterns to read words.
📚 Reading Informational Text (RI)
EE.RI.5.1Identify key details that support the main idea of an informational text.
✍️ Writing (W)
CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.W.5.2.BDevelop the topic with facts, definitions, concrete details, quotations, or other information and examples related to the topic.
CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.W.5.3.CUse a variety of transitional words, phrases, and clauses to manage the sequence of events.
CSS.ELA-LITERACY.W.5.4Produce clear and coherent writing in which the development and organization are appropriate to task, purpose, and audience.

Assessment: Capitalization- https://claude.ai/public/artifacts/84c3b2d2-69b1-4e9b-a12f-cade69453c05

Differentiation: Use these mentor text to talk about transitional words (link in pic):', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
