insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('e4d10650-9943-5898-8a2a-97d129eb678e', 'a3af9977-9ab6-5857-9cb0-68a3faab31db', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d7', 8, 'tue'::weekday, 'Investigating carbonated liquids', 'Investigating carbonated liquids:

Explain to students that so far for this unit there has been a focus on liquids (freezing), solids (melting and now, this session gasses - talking about reversible and irreversible changes.

Have a look at two bottles of water - Sparkling/Still have students taste and describe the bottles of water - small amounts, still water first then sparkly. Ask what they think has been used to make the difference - give them the name/word: carbonated
Today, most commercial soft drinks, seltzers and sparkling waters are created by “forced” carbonation. This is when manufacturers directly inject carbon dioxide into the beverage under high carbon dioxide pressures. A second common way to introduce carbon dioxide into a liquid is by fermentation.
Talk about examples of other carbonated drinks, e.g. 7-UP, soda water, cola, lemonade, etc. Discuss what happens when these drinks are left to ‘go flat’. Where does the gas go? (It escapes into the air.)
They are going to do an experiment:
* For some useful information on this, click on link - Bicarbonate of Soda Experiment

Mix lemon juice and baking soda. What do they notice happening?
Mix baking soda and vinegar? How is the solution changing? Can you get it back?
Then water with baking soda.
Ask them what happened when the lemon juice was added to the baking soda. The mixture starts to bubble up and fizz. Ask them, what is happening? A chemical reaction is taking place, i.e. the molecules in the lemon juice have reacted with those in the bicarbonate to form a gas. Once this gas escapes we can’t get it back, unless you collect it using special equipment – the change is irreversible, the bicarbonate of soda and lemon juice but thinking about last week, the chocolate change when melted by heating is reversible, in that it could be made solid again by cooling.', '[]'::jsonb, 'Note: Day 1 & 2 can be combined - doing as much as can be done. Day 4 & 5 can be combined or as much as can be done taken from these 2 sessions Please make use of the cooking sessions during writing to cover some of the concepts being looked at here.

Std: 5-PS1-2: Measure and graph quantities to provide evidence that regardless of the type of change that occurs when heating, cooling, or mixing substances, the total weight of matter is conserved.

Assessment: What things happen that lets us know a chemical change has taken place

Differentiation: Can name one of the points that indicates a chemical change
Can name 2 points that shows that a chemical change has occurred
Can name more than 2 things that show that a chemical change has taken place.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 6)
