  values ('89a35a73-0ab1-5686-96eb-efb53fa3130e', 'a3af9977-9ab6-5857-9cb0-68a3faab31db', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d7', 8, 'thu'::weekday, 'To start off, have a look at the findings from the previous day - go over the…', 'To start off, have a look at the findings from the previous day - go over the steps and link the carbonated water to the baking soda, talking about the gas that was formed in the chemical reaction and the gas put in carbonated drinks..

Science Fair  Presentation - Baking Soda Expriment.pdf

Today we are going to be learning about thermal conductors.

Start by watching this video, pausing after each section to ask the class questions.
I.e. Why do we use metal pots and pans?
What would happen if we used a metal spoon and left it inside a hot pot?

Conductors and Insulators

Teachers can put hot water in a paper, styrofoam (UK - polystyrene), plastic and glass.. What happens when the cups are heated by putting hot water in them? How do they feel when the water is put in them?

Plan an investigation and carry it out related to the information given in the video about conductors and insulators - Explain if students don’t already know that “thermal” means “the process involving gaining or losing heat”
Make use of the Science Fair template:
Write up for Science Fair', '[]'::jsonb, 'Note: Day 1 & 2 can be combined - doing as much as can be done. Day 4 & 5 can be combined or as much as can be done taken from these 2 sessions Please make use of the cooking sessions during writing to cover some of the concepts being looked at here.

Std: 5-PS1-2: Measure and graph quantities to provide evidence that regardless of the type of change that occurs when heating, cooling, or mixing substances, the total weight of matter is conserved.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 6)
