insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('48040b53-a305-507f-99eb-00e297a2c8f8', 'd4c515d9-c59b-542f-9ca7-d4616717b774', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 15, 'mon'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:

(e.g., "The Boy Who Cried Wolf" and "The Ant and the Grasshopper") or Text in the FOLDER
Warm-Up (3 min) & Lesson (9 min):
Introduction to Researching Skills (15 minutes)
Discuss why research is important when learning about different places.
Teach strategies for finding credible information:
Introduce criteria for evaluating credible sources:
Author: Who wrote it? Are they an expert?
Publication Date: Is the information current?
Bias: Does the source have a particular opinion or agenda?
Purpose: Is the source informative, persuasive, or entertainment-focused?
Guided Research Practice (30 minutes)
Provide a list of recommended kid-friendly resources (print and online).
Assign pairs or small groups to research one of the following:
A geographic feature of the host/home country.
A cultural tradition unique to one of the countries.
Historical connections between the two countries.

Wrap-Up (3 min): Reflect on the research process:
“What was easy or challenging about finding information?”
“How can we make sure our information is trustworthy?”
Rotations:
See list from Sunday or the differentiation section below.', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: Reading Informational Text
RI.5.1 Quote accurately from a text when explaining what the text says explicitly and when drawing inferences from it.
RI.5.2 Determine two or more main ideas of a text and explain how they are supported by key details; summarize the text.
RI.5.9 Integrate information from several texts on the same topic in order to write or speak about the subject knowledgeably.
Writing
W.5.7 Conduct short research projects that use several sources to build knowledge through investigation of different aspects of a topic.
Language
L.5.1.B Form and use the perfect (e.g., I had walked; I have walked; I will have walked) verb tenses.
L.5.1.E Use correlative conjunctions (e.g., either/or, neither/nor).
Reading Informational Text (Essential Elements)
EE.RI.5.1 Identify one or more reasons the author gives to support a point in an informational text.
EE.RI.5.2 Identify the topic and one or more details that support it in an informational text.
Language (Essential Elements)
EE.L.5.1.C Use frequently occurring conjunctions in phrases and simple sentences.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
