insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('46246a5b-98b7-5c29-b2a8-385fff02718f', 'd4c515d9-c59b-542f-9ca7-d4616717b774', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 18, 'tue'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:

Bold Print and Table of Contents

Warm-Up (3 minutes)
Quick Review: Ask students, "What are the text features we’ve discussed so far, and what is the purpose of each?"
Have a few students share, and record student answers on the board.

 Mini-Lesson: Bold Print and Table of Contents (10 minutes)
Text Feature #4: Bold Print: Show examples of bold print from the uploaded material (flip book resource) and a nonfiction book. Ask: "What do you notice about the words in dark, thicker print?" (Bold words point to important words.) Explain: "Bold print helps to make important words and phrases stand out."
Text Feature #5: Table of Contents: Show a variety of tables of contents from different non-fiction texts. Ask: "Where would you look in a book to see what information it contains?" Explain: "The Table of Contents is at the beginning of a book, and it shows you what is in the book and what page it’s on."
Video Clip (2 minutes): Short YouTube video that explains different text features. Example: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1yT55p3W424 (Note: This particular video may need to be adjusted based on your students.) This will provide another avenue for instruction.

 Guided Practice (5 minutes)
Index Cards: Have students use their books to look for examples of bold print and a table of contents. Have them write their examples on an index card. They write the page number and purpose of each on an index card.
Class Share: Have a few students share their findings.

Closing (2 minutes)
Briefly review: "Today, we explored two more important text features. How do bold print and a table of contents help readers?"

Rotations:
See Sunday’s Options', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: Reading Informational Text

RI.3.5 - Use text features and search tools (e.g., key words, sidebars, hyperlinks) to locate information relevant to a given topic efficiently.
RI.3.7 - Use information gained from illustrations (e.g., maps, photographs) and the words in a text to demonstrate understanding of the text (e.g., where, when, why, and how key events occur).
Reading Literature
EE.RL.5.1 – Identify details in a story, drama, or poem to answer questions about a text.
Writing
EE.W.5.9 – Use information from literary or informational texts to support a written response.W.5.8 – Recall relevant information from experiences or gather relevant information from print and digital sources; summarize or paraphrase information in notes and finished work.
Language
L.5.2.C – Use a comma to separate items in a series.EE.L.5.2.E – Spell words phonetically, drawing on knowledge of letter-sound relationships and spelling patterns.

Assessment: Informal- SeeSaw Assignment
Formative through checking for understanding of text features

Differentiation: Support: Provide books with fewer text features or pre-highlighted sections for students who need more support. Also provide a list of the text features on an index card for student reference.

Challenge: Encourage students who need a challenge to use their knowledge to create their own small "informative paragraph" with a heading, label, caption, bold print, and table of contents.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
