insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('3c76190b-9935-58be-a632-aeb73707247e', '3170e847-5264-53cf-bbc6-034ff65e7f0c', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 19, 'sun'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:

Brainpop: Author''s Purpose
Warm-up (5 min)
Ask students: “Why do authors write books? Can you name different reasons?”
Show the PIE anchor chart and explain:
Persuade: convince you of something
Inform: give you facts
Entertain: tell a story for fun
Watch the short video (2 minutes) for a fun explanation.
Practice (7 min)
Read a short passage from The Day the Crayons Quit.
Ask: “What do you think the author’s purpose is? Why?”
Discuss the text’s clues (funny tone, talking crayons, playful story = entertain).
Closing (3 min)
Quick Thumbs Up/Down Game: Teacher says a sentence, and students show thumbs up/down if it persuades, informs, or entertains.
Example:
“Crayons should be used equally, not just blue all the time!” (Persuade)
“Crayons are made from wax and come in many colors.” (Inform)
“The crayons went on strike and wrote letters to their owner!” (Entertain)
Anchor Chart

AND/OR

Rotations:
SeeSaw
PIE Activity
PIE Activity #2
Text features Review
PIE G1 Activity/Reading Comp
Sort (Inform/Entertain)
PIE Practice
Dialogue
Monkey Dialogue

 IXL
G3-Dialogue
G4- Dialogue
G5- Dialogue
G3-Understanding Dialogue
G2-Understanding Dialogue

Google Classroom /Worksheets
Resources/Worksheets

 Boom Cards
Author''s Purpose
Author’s Purpose 2

Claude

RazKids, EPIC, Book Bag
Writing
Kahoot
Dialogue
Dialogue #2', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: RI.5.6 – Analyze multiple accounts of the same event or topic, noting important similarities and differences in the point of view they represent.
EE.RI.5.6 – Identify how points of view differ in texts about the same topic.
RI.5.8 – Explain how an author uses reasons and evidence to support particular points in a text.
W.5.1 – Write opinion pieces on topics or texts, supporting a point of view with reasons and information.
EE.RI.5.1 – Identify evidence to support understanding of a text.
EE.RI.5.3 – Identify relationships among ideas or events in a text.
L.5.2.B – Use a comma to separate items in a series.
EE.L.5.2.G – Use basic capitalization, punctuation, and spelling.

Assessment: Writing:
Observe student participation during discussions and activities.
Formative: Listen to student responses in the Thumbs Up/Down Game to check understanding.
Grammar: SeeSaw and Worksheets

Differentiation: Writing:
Support: Provide sentence starters (e.g., "I think____ because ____," "My opinion is ____ because ____"). Help students generate reasons through guided questioning.
Challenge: Encourage students to use more descriptive language for their reasons. Ask them to add a concluding sentence to summarize their idea.

Reading:
For struggling students: Provide a PIE anchor chart for reference.

For advanced students: Let them brainstorm their own PIE examples.

Grammar:
Provide a version of the story with dialogue already underlined for struggling readers.
Challenge advanced students to explain the use of commas and punctuation within the dialogue.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
