insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('3f59076d-d18c-5ac0-9f48-2e8388e973a9', '3170e847-5264-53cf-bbc6-034ff65e7f0c', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 19, 'mon'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:
Warm-up (5 min)
Ask: “Has anyone ever convinced you to buy something? How?”
Watch persuasive writing video (2 minutes).
Practice (7 min)
Read a short advertisement (e.g., “This toy is the best! Everyone loves it! Buy yours today!”).
Ask: “What is the author trying to do?” (Persuade)
Discuss persuasive techniques (opinion words, emotional appeal, facts).
Have students write their own 2-sentence persuasive ad on whiteboards.
Closing (3 min)
Share a few persuasive ads.
Ask: “What words did they use to persuade?”
Mentor Text:
Hey Little Ant by Phillip and Hannah Hoose
Don''t Let the Pigeon Drive The Bus by Mo Willems
The Great Kapok Tree by Lynne Cherry
Earrings by Judith Viorst
One Word from Sophia by Jim Averbeck and Yasmeen Ismail', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: RI.5.6 – Analyze multiple accounts of the same event or topic, noting important similarities and differences in the point of view they represent.
EE.RI.5.6 – Identify how points of view differ in texts about the same topic.
RI.5.8 – Explain how an author uses reasons and evidence to support particular points in a text.
W.5.1 – Write opinion pieces on topics or texts, supporting a point of view with reasons and information.
EE.RI.5.1 – Identify evidence to support understanding of a text.
EE.RI.5.3 – Identify relationships among ideas or events in a text.
L.5.2.B – Use a comma to separate items in a series.
EE.L.5.2.G – Use basic capitalization, punctuation, and spelling.

Assessment: Writing:
Observe student participation during discussions and activities.
Formative: Ask students to give examples or samples of persuasive writing.
Grammar: Grammar: SeeSaw and Worksheets

Differentiation: Writing:
Support: Provide sentence starters (e.g., "I think____ because ____," "My opinion is ____ because ____"). Help students generate reasons through guided questioning.
Challenge: Encourage students to use more descriptive language for their reasons. Ask them to add a concluding sentence to summarize their idea.

Reading: For struggling students: Provide a word bank of persuasive words.
For advanced students: Have them write a longer persuasive sentence.

Grammar: Provide sentence frames: “____,” said ____.

Challenge advanced students to replace “said” with stronger verbs (e.g., exclaimed, whispered).', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
