insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('9430cf25-0129-5299-9c6c-4fae1b1fc7da', '3170e847-5264-53cf-bbc6-034ff65e7f0c', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 19, 'wed'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:

Warm-up (5 min)
Show two books: One nonfiction (Why Do Snakes Shed Their Skin?) and one fiction (There’s a snake in my school)
Ask: “Which one gives facts? How do you know?”
Review informational text features (headings, facts, pictures).
Practice (7 min)
Read a short passage from an article (e.g., about sharks).
Ask: “What is the purpose? What clues tell us this?”
Students find three facts in the passage and share.
Closing (3 min)
Students pick up a nonfiction book and find one fact to share.', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: RI.5.6 – Analyze multiple accounts of the same event or topic, noting important similarities and differences in the point of view they represent.
EE.RI.5.6 – Identify how points of view differ in texts about the same topic.
RI.5.8 – Explain how an author uses reasons and evidence to support particular points in a text.
W.5.1 – Write opinion pieces on topics or texts, supporting a point of view with reasons and information.
EE.RI.5.1 – Identify evidence to support understanding of a text.
EE.RI.5.3 – Identify relationships among ideas or events in a text.
L.5.2.B – Use a comma to separate items in a series.
EE.L.5.2.G – Use basic capitalization, punctuation, and spelling.

Assessment: Writing:
Observe student participation during discussions and activities.

Formative: Listen to student explanations of why a text is entertaining.

Grammar:Review student writing for correct punctuation.

Punctuation Practice: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Rpf_niPOWlLtfrkzVvC2po-Eyvut8mfHkqQ9cZlFf_g/edit#slide=id.p

Differentiation: Writing:
Support: Provide sentence starters (e.g., "I think____ because ____," "My opinion is ____ because ____"). Help students generate reasons through guided questioning.
Challenge: Encourage students to use more descriptive language for their reasons. Ask them to add a concluding sentence to summarize their idea.

Reading: For struggling students: Provide a list of story elements to guide discussion.

For advanced students: Have them write their own short entertaining sentences.

Grammar: Provide sentence starters for struggling writers.
Challenge advanced students to use multiple speakers.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
