insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('038476d4-a691-5815-baeb-a126b52109eb', '3170e847-5264-53cf-bbc6-034ff65e7f0c', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 20, 'tue'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:
Warm-up (5 min) – Video Clip Predictions
Show a short video, Those Shoes
Pause halfway and ask: "What do you predict will happen next?"
Discuss why they made that prediction.
Practice (7 min) – Guided Reading with Predictions
Read the first few paragraphs of a story (e.g., Owl Moon by Jane Yolen).
Pause at key moments and ask:
What will happen next?
What clues support your prediction?
Students write predictions on whiteboards.
Closing (3 min) – Reflect
Students update or revise their predictions based on new details.', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: RL5.1 – Quote accurately from a text when explaining what the text says explicitly and when drawing inferences.
RI5.1 – Quote accurately from a text when explaining what the text says explicitly and when drawing inferences.
EE.RL5.1 – Identify explicit details and make logical inferences from a literary text.
EE.RI5.1 – Identify explicit details and make logical inferences from an informational text.
CC: L.5.1.C – Use verb tense to convey various times, sequences, states, and conditions.
EE.L.5.1.K – Use correct verb tense in sentences.
RI5.8 – Explain how an author uses reasons and evidence to support particular points in a text.
W5.1 – Write opinion pieces supporting a point of view with reasons and information.
W5.2a – Introduce a topic clearly, group related information logically, and include formatting, illustrations, or multimedia when useful.
EE.RI5.2 – Identify the main idea of an informational text and recount key details.

Assessment: Reading- Observe participation in discussions

Grammar-
Oral quiz: Call on students to say the pronoun that matches a noun given by the teacher.
Quick write: "Write one sentence with ''he'' and one with ''they.''"

Differentiation: Reading- Pause & discuss for struggling readers
Use graphic organizers for structured predictions

Grammar-
Support: Use picture cards of boys/girls/animals to help students select the correct pronoun.
Challenge: Discuss how "they" can be used for one person or a group.

Writing:
Support: Record ideas as a group & then students can write ideas on sheet.
Challenge: Students record their own ideas with some help with structuring the point being put across.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
