  values ('2ec80a7e-762c-5932-895c-846f4d0b71ae', '3170e847-5264-53cf-bbc6-034ff65e7f0c', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 21, 'wed'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:
Warm-up (3 minutes):
Review the anchor chart from Day 1.
Play Fact or Opinion? Move right or left Game
Practice (10 minutes):
Show two short commercials (one with facts, one with opinions).
https://kids.nationalgeographic.com/
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Le68Nj_nVzU
Ask: Which statements are facts? Which are opinions?
Group activity: Students sort printed statements from "Fact" or "Opinion" categories.', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: RI.5.8 – Explain how an author uses reasons and evidence to support particular points in a text.
EE.RI.5.8 – Identify the reasons an author gives to support points in a text.
L.5.3.A – Expand, combine, and reduce sentences for meaning, reader interest, and style.
EE.L.5.3.A – Use language to achieve meaning and clarity when writing or speaking.
RI.5.9 – Integrate information from several texts on the same topic in order to write or speak about the subject knowledgeably.
W.5.2a – Introduce a topic clearly, provide a general observation and focus, and group related information logically.
W.5.8 – Recall relevant information from experiences or gather relevant information from print and digital sources and summarize or paraphrase information in notes and finished work.
EE.RI.5.2 – Identify the main idea of a text and retell key details.
EE.RI.5.3 – Compare two or more individuals, events, or ideas in a text based on specific information.

Assessment: Reading- Discuss: Why do advertisements use opinions more than facts?
Ticket Out the Door: Write one opinion an ad might use to sell a product.

Grammar- Whiteboard Check: Call out a sentence. Students hold up whiteboards with their revised version.

Writing: Informally assess class participation and students’ ability to support opinions

Differentiation: Reading-
Struggling learners: Provide pre-written statements and guide sorting.
Advanced learners: Challenge them to write their own advertisement using both facts and opinions.

Grammar-Struggling students: Provide sentence stems to guide conversions.
Advanced students: Have them create a short paragraph using both voices.

Writing:
LA: Give sentence starters for opinion writing.
HA: Challenge them to predict responses before surveying and justify their predictions in writing.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
