Warm-Up/Practice ((3 min):
Quick review: What’s the difference between summarizing and paraphrasing?
Play a sorting game: Give students examples of sentences and have them decide if they are summaries or paraphrases.
Read a short informational passage.
Quick Review/Check:
Step 1: Have students summarize the paragraph in one sentence.
Step 2: Have students paraphrase one sentence from the paragraph.
Compare: How are they different?', '[]'::jsonb, 'Std: RI.5.2 – Determine two or more main ideas of a text and explain how they are supported by key details; summarize the text.
EE.RI.5.2 – Identify the main idea of a text and summarize key details.
W.5.1 – Write opinion pieces on topics or texts, supporting a point of view with reasons and information.
W.5.4 – Produce clear and coherent writing in which the development, organization, and style are appropriate to task, purpose, and audience.
W.5.9 – Draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support analysis,

Assessment: Reading- Exit ticket: Students write one sentence explaining the difference between summarizing and paraphrasing.

Grammar- Exit Ticket: Write a sentence using a conjunction, preposition, and pronoun.
Reflection: How do these parts of speech help connect ideas in writing?

Writing
Review the written summaries and opinion paragraphs.
Is the summary accurate and concise?
Does the opinion paragraph express a clear opinion with supporting reasons?

Differentiation: Reading- Struggling learners: Provide examples of paraphrased and summarized sentences for guidance.
