insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('53a748a4-9eb5-5963-95ed-67c8d68cb43d', '5acb9a7c-064f-5202-bb5d-cd2db57e15fe', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 23, 'mon'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:

ComprehensionPrintablesIdoWedoYoudo.pdf

The teacher and students will practice reading comprehension strategies within small groups or as a whole group. The teacher will be sure to have students identify skills that help in the understanding of the text. (See Below)
Before Reading (Pre-Reading Strategies)
Activating Prior Knowledge – Connect the text to what students already know.
Predicting – Make predictions based on the title, pictures, or prior knowledge.
Previewing the Text – Skim headings, images, and captions to get an overview.
Setting a Purpose for Reading – Define why they are reading (e.g., to learn, to enjoy, to find information).
During Reading (Active Reading Strategies)
Asking Questions – Encourage “who, what, where, when, why, how” questions.
Visualizing – Create mental images of what is happening in the text.
Making Connections – Text-to-self, text-to-text, and text-to-world connections.
Summarizing – Identify key details and main ideas in a few sentences.
Using Context Clues – Decode unfamiliar words based on surrounding text.
Making Inferences – Read between the lines to understand hidden meanings.
Rereading for Clarity – Go back and read again to improve understanding.
Identifying Main Idea and Supporting Details – Find the central message and key facts.
Monitoring Comprehension – Stop and reflect on understanding; use "fix-up" strategies if confused.
After Reading (Post-Reading Strategies)
Summarizing and Retelling – Recount the story in their own words.
Drawing Conclusions – Use text evidence to form opinions or conclusions.
Answering Comprehension Questions – Respond to literal, inferential, and critical thinking questions.
Discussing and Sharing – Participate in partner or group discussions about the text.
Making Connections to Real Life – Relate the story to personal experiences.
Creating a Graphic Organizer – Use Venn diagrams, story maps, or flowcharts to organize ideas.
Writing a Response – Reflect through writing (e.g., journal entry, letter, or opinion piece).', '[]'::jsonb, 'Note: 1. Dates: Rates: (As in, judging or appreciating something; could be used in a poem about appreciating the blessings of dates.) Gates: (Gates of Paradise, gates to the mosque, gates to the house.) States: (As in conditions, describing the different states of fasting or spirituality.) 2. Mosque: Kiosk: (Though not directly Islamic, mosques often have a small kiosk selling religious items.) Disk: (Could be a symbolic reference to knowledge or wisdom gained at the mosque) 3. Prayer: Carer: (Emphasis on the care and devotion put into prayer) Sharer: (Linking prayers to sharing a special time) 4. Star: Far: (Relating to how far the light of guidance can travel, or the distance to Mecca.) 5. Moon: Soon: (Ramadan will be here soon, or the end of fasting day is coming soon.) 6. Iftar: Gifter: (Allah is the ultimate giver, and we are grateful for the Iftar meal.) After: (The time after a long day of fasting.)

Std: L.5.4.C (CCSS)
Consult reference materials (e.g., dictionaries, glossaries, thesauruses), both print and digital, to find the pronunciation and determine or clarify the precise meaning of key words and phrases.
L.5.4 (CCSS)
Determine or clarify the meaning of unknown and multiple-meaning words and phrases based on grade 5 reading and content, choosing flexibly from a range of strategies.
W.5.1.A (CCSS)
Introduce a topic or text clearly, state an opinion, and create an organizational structure in which ideas are logically grouped to support the writer’s purpose.
EE.5.1.1.A (Essential Element)
Introduce a topic or text and state an opinion about it.
W.5.1.B (CCSS)
Provide logically ordered reasons that are supported by facts and details.
EE.5.1.1.B (Essential Element)
Provide at least one reason to support an opinion.
W.5.2.A (CCSS)
Introduce a topic clearly, provide a general observation and focus, and group related information logically; include formatting (e.g., headings), illustrations, and multimedia when useful to aiding

Assessment: Grammar- Quick class discussion: "Which part of the dictionary entry is most useful to you?"
Partner quiz: One student asks, "What is the part of speech for ___?" The other answers.

Writing:
Observe accuracy in identifying the ABAB rhyme scheme.

Differentiation: Grammar-  Support: Provide pre-highlighted dictionary entries and have students match terms (e.g., underline part of speech).
Challenge: Ask students to find a word with multiple meanings and explain how the meanings differ.

Writing:
Support: Start with poems that are visually simple to understand, use colors to highlight.
Challenge: Ask students to create their own ABAB example.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 1)
