insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('67133155-ad96-5d78-8e30-117261bbe785', '5acb9a7c-064f-5202-bb5d-cd2db57e15fe', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d2', 25, 'sun'::weekday, 'Guided Reading', 'Guided Reading:

Warm-Up: (whole group)
The teacher will begin the lesson by briefly reviewing the reading and comprehension skills that were learned in previous classes. This may include identifying characters, setting, plot, and understanding the sequence of events in a story.

Practice:
Reading and comprehension activity: The teacher will provide each group of students with a text that is appropriate for their reading level. This may be a short story, a chapter from a book, a poem, or an informational text. The students will read the text in their groups, discussing the characters, setting, plot, and main ideas. The teacher will circulate around the room, offering support and guidance as needed..  (Can also be done in Guided Reading)

Wrap Up:
The teacher will summarize the main points of the lesson, reinforcing the importance of reading comprehension and summarizing as essential skills for understanding a text. The teacher may review the different strategies for summarizing and how they help identify the main ideas of a text.

Rotations:
SeeSaw
Homographs
Draw your homograph
Homophones
Homophones
Homophones

 IXL
G3 Homophones
G4 Homophones
G5 Homophones
G3 Match Sentence
G4 Match Sentence

Google Classroom /Worksheets
Homophones/Homographs

 Boom Cards
RazKids, EPIC, Book Bag
Writing
Kahoot', '[]'::jsonb, 'Note: Example Haiku: Rain Soft rain is falling Washing the world with new life Green plants rise above

Std: CCW.5.7  Conduct short research projects that use several sources to build knowledge through investigation of different aspects of a topic.
CCW.5.8  Recall relevant information from experiences or gather relevant information from print and digital sources. Summarize or paraphrase information in notes and finished work and provide a list of sources.
CCW.5.9   Draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support analysis, reflection, and research.
EE5.1.3.A  Identify two or more individuals, events, ideas, or concepts in a text.
EE5.1.3.B  Identify how individuals, events, ideas, or concepts are related in a text.
L.5.4.C  Consult reference materials (dictionaries, glossaries, thesauruses) to determine or clarify the meaning of words and phrases.
L.5.5.C  Use the relationship between particular words (synonyms, antonyms, homographs) to better understand each word.

Assessment: Grammar-Students write a sentence using a homophone pair of their choice.

Writing: Observe student engagement in the discussion and their ability to repeat the syllable structure.

Differentiation: Grammar-Support: Provide picture clues for struggling students.
Challenge: Ask advanced students to write short stories using at least three homophones.

Writing - Support: Pre-printed cards with the syllable structure (5-7-5) and a visual representation. Provide pre-counted syllables for students to read and practice.

