insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('7bd1eca2-8038-5b82-8a6d-3fbd85b99e9d', 'd35d79bf-6c35-5d29-b7ea-3d67b1b9ff0e', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d7', 30, 'thu'::weekday, 'Light Detectives: How Does Light Travel?', 'Light Detectives: How Does Light Travel?

Materials
For each group (approx. 4-5 students):
1 Light source (e.g., flashlight/torch – ensure batteries are working)
3-4 Small, safe mirrors (plastic or handheld cosmetic mirrors)
A small collection of objects:
Opaque: e.g., wooden block, thick cardboard shape, book
Translucent: e.g., piece of coloured plastic, thin tissue paper, maybe tracing paper
1 piece of White card or paper (as a target screen)
A room that can be partially or fully darkened.
(5 mins)
Thinking About Light
We know light helps us see. But how does light get from a lamp (point) or the Sun all the way to our eyes?"
"Remember talking about shadows? What makes a shadow?" (Something blocking the light). "Does this give us a clue about how light travels? If something blocks it, maybe light travels..." (Guide towards "straight").
Posing the Puzzle: "So, light seems to travel straight. But can we make light bend or turn corners? What do you think?" (Accept initial ideas). "Today, we''re going to be Light Detectives and investigate!"
(20 mins)
 Explore & Explain: Light Maze Challenge
Group Up & Materials: Divide class into pre-arranged groups. Distribute the light source, mirrors, objects, and white card to each group.
The Challenge: "Here''s your mission, Light Detectives! Place your white card somewhere nearby. Your challenge is to get the light from your flashlight to shine onto the white card, BUT you cannot point the flashlight directly at the card! You MUST use your mirrors and maybe the other objects to guide the light beam."
Safety First: Be gentle with the mirrors."
Darken the Room: Dim the lights as much as practical to make the light beams visible.
Investigation Time: Allow groups 10-15 minutes to experiment. Circulate and ask guiding questions:
"What happens when the light hits the mirror?" (It bounces off / changes direction). Introduce the word reflect.
"Can you make the light hit the card using just one mirror?"
"Now try using two mirrors. Can you make the light turn a corner?"
"What happens when the light beam hits the wooden block? Does it go through?" (No, it''s blocked). Introduce opaque. "What do you see behind the block?" (A shadow).
"What happens when the light hits the coloured plastic/tissue paper?" (Some light goes through, it might be coloured/dimmer). Do introduce the word translucent.
"Does the light beam look as bright after bouncing off many mirrors?" (Maybe not).
Bringing it Together (Mid-Experiment Pause if needed): Briefly get class attention. "What are you using to make the light change direction?" (Mirrors!). "Is the light bending by itself, or is it bouncing off the mirrors?" (Bouncing/Reflecting).
(10 mins)
Sharing Findings & Space Connection
Light Back On/Gather Attention: Bring the lights back up slightly. Have groups stop experimenting and focus.
Feedback Discussion (using prompt questions):
"How were you able to change the way the light travelled?" (Using mirrors to reflect it).
"Could you make it bend around corners?" (Yes, by reflecting it!). Reinforce: Light travels straight until it hits something.
"Was the type of material important?" (Yes! Mirrors reflect, opaque blocks, translucent lets some through).
"Did you see shadows? What shape were they?" (Yes, same shape as the opaque object).
"Did the light beam change?" (Maybe got dimmer/weaker after reflecting many times or going further).
Connecting to the Moon: Show the image of the Moon. "Think about our Moon. Does it make its own light like the Sun or a lamp?" (No). "So how can we see it shining so brightly at night?"
The BIG Reveal: Show the Sun -> Moon -> Earth diagram. "It''s just like your experiment! The Sun is the light source. Light travels in a straight line from the Sun, hits the Moon, and then reflects (bounces) off the Moon in straight lines towards our eyes on Earth! We see the Moon because it''s reflecting sunlight."
Other Space Objects: "Planets and even comets that we see also shine because they are reflecting sunlight, just like the Moon!"
(5 mins)
Evaluate: Checking Understanding/Recap: "So, light travels in ______ lines. Mirrors ______ light. Opaque objects ______ light and make shadows. We see the Moon because it ______ sunlight." (Fill in blanks: straight, reflect, block, reflects).', '["To be able to::", "State that light appears to travel in straight lines.", "Demonstrate that mirrors can change the direction of light (reflection).", "Distinguish between opaque objects (which block light and create shadows) and translucent objects (which let some light through).", "Explain that we see the Moon because it reflects sunlight."]'::jsonb, 'Note: Qatar (Doha) June 1st, 2024: Sunrise: 04:43, Sunset: 18:21 = Daylight Duration: 13 hours 38 minutes June 15th, 2024: Sunrise: 04:43, Sunset: 18:25 = Daylight Duration: 13 hours 42 minutes June 30th, 2024: Sunrise: 04:47, Sunset: 18:29 = Daylight Duration: 13 hours 42 minutes December 1st, 2024: Sunrise: 06:03, Sunset: 16:42 = Daylight Duration: 10 hours 39 minutes December 15th, 2024: Sunrise: 06:12, Sunset: 16:45 = Daylight Duration: 10 hours 33 minutes December 31st, 2024: Sunrise: 06:20, Sunset: 16:54 = Daylight Duration: 10 hours 34 minutes United Kingdom (London) June 1st, 2024: Sunrise: ~04:52, Sunset: ~21:08 = Daylight Duration: ~16 hours 16 minutes June 15th, 2024: Sunrise: ~04:43, Sunset: ~21:20 = Daylight Duration: ~16 hours 37 minutes June 30th, 2024: Sunrise: ~04:53, Sunset: ~21:18 = Daylight Duration: ~16 hours 25 minutes December 1st, 2024: Sunrise: ~07:44, Sunset: ~15:56 = Daylight Duration: ~8 hours 12 minutes December 15th, 2024: Sunrise: ~08:02, Sunset: ~15:53 = Daylight Duration: ~7 hours 51 minutes December 31st, 2024: Sunrise: ~08:08, Sunset: ~16:05 = Daylight Duration: ~7 hours 57 minutes United States (New York City) June 1st, 2024: Sunrise: ~05:26, Sunset: ~20:24 = Daylight Duration: ~14 hours 58 minutes June 15th, 2024: Sunrise: ~05:23, Sunset: ~20:32 = Daylight Duration: ~15 hours 9 minutes June 30th, 2024: Sunrise: ~05:31, Sunset: ~20:32 = Daylight Duration: ~15 hours 1 minute December 1st, 2024: Sunrise: ~07:04, Sunset: ~16:32 = Daylight Duration: ~9 hours 28 minutes December 15th, 2024: Sunrise: ~07:17, Sunset: ~16:29 = Daylight Duration: ~9 hours 12 minutes December 31st, 2024: Sunrise: ~07:20, Sunset: ~16:39 = Daylight Duration: ~9 hours 19 minutes Australia (Sydney) June 1st, 2024: Sunrise: ~06:54, Sunset: ~16:54 = Daylight Duration: ~10 hours 0 minutes June 15th, 2024: Sunrise: ~06:59, Sunset: ~16:50 = Daylight Duration: ~9 hours 51 minutes June 30th, 2024: Sunrise: ~07:06, Sunset: ~16:52 = Daylight Duration: ~9 hours 46 minutes December 1st, 2024: Sunrise: ~05:42, Sunset: ~20:03 = Daylight Duration: ~14 hours 21 minutes December 15th, 2024: Sunrise: ~05:38, Sunset: ~20:12 = Daylight Duration: ~14 hours 34 minutes December 31st, 2024: Sunrise: ~05:42, Sunset: ~20:22 = Daylight Duration: ~14 hours 40 minutes Japan (Tokyo) June 1st, 2024: Sunrise: 04:26, Sunset: 18:52 = Daylight Duration: 14 hours 26 minutes June 15th, 2024: Sunrise: 04:25, Sunset: 18:59 = Daylight Duration: 14 hours 34 minutes June 30th, 2024: Sunrise: 04:28, Sunset: 19:01 = Daylight Duration: 14 hours 33 minutes December 1st, 2024: Sunrise: 06:32, Sunset: 16:28 = Daylight Duration: 9 hours 56 minutes December 15th, 2024: Sunrise: 06:43, Sunset: 16:29 = Daylight Duration: 9 hours 46 minutes December 31st, 2024: Sunrise: 06:50, Sunset: 16:38 = Daylight Duration: 9 hours 48 minutes

Assessment: Activity: Thumbs up/down: "Light travels straight?" (Up). "Mirrors bend light?" (Down - they reflect). "We see the Moon because it makes light?" (Down). "We can see the Moon because it reflects light" (Up).

Differentiation: Support:
Provide diagrams showing simple one-mirror reflections as a guide.
Focus vocabulary on "bounce," "block," "goes through."

Challenge:
Challenge groups to hit the target using three mirrors.', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 6)
