insert into master_core_lesson_events
  (id, unit_id, subject_id, week_number, day_of_week, title, directions, learning_objectives, notes, resources, standards, display_order_within_day)
  values ('9e6f61a6-6bd9-5f52-bb50-97b65dd18b3d', 'd35d79bf-6c35-5d29-b7ea-3d67b1b9ff0e', '00000000-0000-0000-0000-0000000005d7', 34, 'tue'::weekday, 'Key Vocabulary', 'Key Vocabulary
Bar graph, Data, Most, Least, Oceans, Ice, Lakes, Rivers

Which Stack Is Taller? (5 minutes)
Create three stacks of cubes.
Ask:
“Which stack has the most cubes?”
“How do you know?”
Explicit Teaching (10 minutes)
Display the assessment graph.
Teach:
Read the labels.
Look at the height of each bar.
The tallest bar represents the greatest amount.
Identify:
Oceans = tallest bar
Ice = medium bar
Lakes and rivers = shortest bar
 Guided Practice (10 minutes)
Ask:
Which bar is tallest?
Which has the least?
Which category has the most water?
Students point out which is which.
Data Talk (10 minutes)
Students to give varying points about the graph using “data talk”:
The tallest bar shows the most
The least is shown by the shortest bar
There are more oceans than ice because…
Rivers are less than…
Exit Ticket (5 minutes)
Students answer:
“Where is most of Earth’s water found?”
Finish off after responses recorded:
Over 96%–97% of Earth''s water is found in the oceans. This saline water covers roughly 71% of the Earth''s surface. While the oceans are the largest reservoir, the remaining 3% is freshwater, mostly locked in glaciers and ice caps.', '["Identify which bar shows the greatest amount.", "Success Criteria", "I can read a bar graph.", "I can find the tallest bar.", "I can tell which category has the most."]'::jsonb, 'Note: No Exhibition this year

Std: Read and interpret simple graphs.
Compare quantities using visual data.
Understand that most of Earth’s water is found in the oceans.

Assessment Opportunities
Oral questioning
Exit sentence

Differentiation: Support
Highlight the tallest bar
Provide sentence frame:
“The tallest bar is ______.”
Extension
Encourage students to compare all categories:
“Oceans have more water than ice and lakes.”', '[]'::jsonb, '{}'::uuid[], 6)
